english:
  title: A Discourse Refuting Geomantic Superstition
  author: Eo Hyocheomp
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your subject has not read widely in books on geomancy, and what little he has read slips from memory as soon as the pages are closed. The essential principles elude me, and my learning being shallow, I possess no real understanding. Yet in my simple-minded obstinacy, I have come to believe that the teachings of geomancy did not exist before the Three Dynasties. Thus in the Yili, which records the institutions of the Duke of Zhou, there is only the divination of burial sites and auspicious days. Did not Confucius himself say merely that "the burial site is divined and the funeral conducted"? Only after the Han dynasties did such arts arise, each school establishing its own theories of fortune and misfortune, thereby deceiving the world and deluding the people. When Emperor Taizong of Tang saw that the occult writings on yin-yang were riddled with errors and superstitious taboos abounded, he commanded the Grand Luminary Lü Cai to correct and remove such falsehoods. Lü Cai completed this work and wrote commentaries grounded in the Classics and Histories, which scholars have recognized as sound doctrine. Regarding burial, his account states: "The ancients buried their dead to the north of their capitals, with fixed burial grounds—there was no selecting of sites. Now through the false words of shamans, people select burial grounds and choose auspicious times during their grief, hoping to gain wealth and rank." Since Lü Cai spoke thus, even in Tang times such practices were merely the livelihood of shamans and sorcerers, believed by the ignorant masses but rejected by learned scholars.

    In the Song Dynasty, Sima Guang discussed burial and wrote: "The vulgar trust in geomancers' words, selecting year, month, day, and hour, and also examining the forms of mountains and waters. Even if such things could truly bring fortune or disaster to people, how could one bear to expose one's parents to wind and rain while seeking personal gain? Yet a filial child's heart is deeply concerned with the future, and thus seeks places with thick earth and deep water for burial." The great sage Cheng Yi, in his discourse on burial, stated: "To divine the burial site means to divine whether the ground is auspicious or inauspicious—not what the yin-yang specialists call fortune and misfortune. Yet those obsessed with taboos determine the fortune of days by the direction of the burial site. Is this not being bound by superstition?" When Hu Yong asked Zhu Xi about this, saying, "When the time comes to conduct the funeral, we again consult divination—this mountain is inauspicious, that water is inauspicious. Once we have mountains and waters embracing the site before us, and we examine the fortune of approach and departure, and require that year, month, day, and hour all accord with such sayings, must it truly be so complicated?" Zhu Xi replied: "The site need only have proper form—mountains and waters embracing and protecting it with no vacant spaces. That suffices for use. What is unnecessary is this business of 'this mountain' and 'that water.'" From this we see that even the great worthies and scholars of the flourishing Song rejected such theories of geomantic fortune and misfortune. All of this is recorded in the Classics and Histories and can be verified point by point—surely Your Highness already comprehends this fully. Would your subject dare deceive you?

    If such theories of fortune and misfortune are unsuitable even for burial grounds, how much more unsuitable are they for the capital city itself? The length of a dynasty's rule and the fortune of a nation depend upon Heaven's mandate and the hearts of the people—they have nothing to do with geomancy. Therefore did the worthy ministers of old warn their sovereigns, saying first: "Heaven's favor is not constant to one person alone—it sends a hundred blessings upon those who do good and a hundred calamities upon those who do evil." Second: "Heaven has no partiality; it draws near to the reverent. The people have no fixed allegiance; they follow the benevolent." And third: "I cannot but observe the house of Xia, nor can I but observe the house of Shang. It was through disrespect for their virtue that their mandate of Heaven fell early." These are unchanging truths.

    Moreover, before the Three Dynasties, there was no such geomantic art, yet nations endured long and governance flourished gloriously, surpassing all later times. Can it be that all their capital sites happened to conform to modern geomantic theories? Consider: the capitals at Chang'an—the Western Han lasted 214 years, the Western Wei, Later Zhou, and Sui under the High Ancestor each lasted some twenty years, and the Tang endured 290 years. At Luoyang—the Eastern Han lasted 196 years, Cao Wei and Western Jin lasted forty to fifty years, and Sui under the Yangdi merely thirteen years. At Jiankang—the Eastern Jin lasted 105 years, while Song, Qi, Liang, and Chen lasted between thirty and sixty years each. At Kaifeng—the Five Dynasties were short-lived, lasting but ten years or even four, while the Song endured 167 years. Thus we see that though the capital was sometimes the same, the length of each dynasty's rule varied greatly. This is why I say that national fortune bears no relation to geomancy.

    Yet some claim that blocking the northern road brings blessing while opening it brings calamity, or that filling in the slopes within the city brings good fortune while leaving them brings misfortune. Upon what teaching or precedent do such claims rest? Your subject, being ignorant, cannot fathom this reasoning. The ancient imperial system required the court to face south and the marketplace to face north, so was the area north of the palace entirely forbidden to human passage? Moreover, geomancers speak of the harm caused both by severed city walls and blocked roads. Yet observe the palace foundations—they descend nearly a fathom into the earth. If we accept the geomancers' logic that the city wall severs the vital vein to this depth, surely forbidding people to walk upon its surface would be trivial. And to add soil to an already severed vein is like grafting flesh onto a wound—how could the vital channels flow? If one truly wished to restore such flow, blocking the northern road would not suffice, nor would building up slopes within the city help. One would first need to destroy the palace itself—yet can the palace be destroyed? This is clearly impossible.

    Consider the text "Illuminating the Cavern," compiled by Fan Yuefeng of the Five Dynasties. Regarding burial sites, he speaks of foul and unclean waters as signs of calamity and depravity. But he does not extend such principles to the capital city. His reasoning was simply that the sacred way demands cleanliness, and unclean water disturbs the spirits—this applies to burial, not to cities. For cities, with their dense populations and accumulated filth, require channels and streams to carry away such refuse for the realm to remain clean. How can city water be as pure as mountain springs? If we demand it, neither circumstance nor reason permits it. Death and life follow different paths; spirits and humans have different natures. Can principles for burial grounds be applied to the capital city?

    If our capital's form accords perfectly with geomantic theory, then why should these few matters remain deficient? If the capital has many aspects that do not conform to such theory, yet all geomantic principles can be applied everywhere, then no one could dwell within the burial grounds. Should the city's entire population be removed outside the walls? Moreover, Gyeongbok Palace and Changdeok Palace are specially near the inner sanctums—could their inhabitants be entirely evacuated? The texts say that where the Four Celestial Guardians cross, death awaits; where the Four Directions cross, poverty comes; where roads cross in the southwestern sector, debauchery flourishes; where roads cross in the northeastern sector, children die. Should we then block all gates and roads aligned with these sectors? Such examples are endless. If one cannot fully follow such arts, why fixate on these few matters alone? This is what your humble subject cannot understand.

    When false teachings arise, they easily deceive the people, for they work through the lever of fortune and misfortune. Merely tell the masses, "That mountain and that water bring disaster to the realm," and they will reply, "How could a loyal subject bear it?" None dare resist. This is because the heart has been moved by the specter of fortune and misfortune. Yet the Duke of Zhou and Confucius were the greatest sages under Heaven, and Sima Guang, Cheng Yi, and Zhu Xi were the greatest worthies. Regarding fortune and misfortune: the former did not speak of it, and the latter did not accept it. If they failed to speak because they knew it not, then they were ignorant; if they knew it yet did not speak, then they were disloyal. If they knew it yet rejected it, then they too were disloyal. Would these two sages and three worthies alone have failed to be loyal servants? Then do the sages and worthies prove less wise and less loyal than the geomancers? This logic is beyond doubt and accords with sacred learning. Would your subject dare deceive you?

    Though creating artificial hills and blocking roads might cause no immediate harm, they violate the Way of the sages and worthies. And what of their pernicious consequences in later generations? Now above reigns a sagacious ruler, and below stands his sage heir as crown prince, assisted by virtuous ministers deliberating upon governance and establishing laws to guide ten thousand generations. This is precisely the time when, as it is said, the sage before Confucius cannot be understood without Confucius, and the sage after Confucius has no standard but Confucius. If we now employ such arts, future generations will say, "My ancestor was a sage and accepted this practice—how dare I, being unworthy, violate his precedent?" Thus will all human fortune and misfortune, rank and station, wisdom and folly, longevity and early death become bound to these practices. The ruler will believe, the minister will be confused, and crafty fraudsters will seize their chance to declare, "That district requires relocation of residents. That direction needs blocking. This peak should be raised, that valley lowered"—inverting fortune and misfortune to dupe the people. Not only this, but later the theories of previous dynasties regarding geomantic amendment might resurface, with calls to build temples here and erect pagodas there. Once the heart is clouded, vision dims, and rulers and ministers together fall into the snare of artifice. They would then believe that through such techniques they can extend their dynasty's years, neglecting to cultivate virtue while seeking to secure Heaven's mandate through these means. Thus would today's actions fail to constitute true planning for the inheritance of descendants. Should this not be treated with utmost care?

    Our Great King Taejong issued a royal decree saying: "The ancient kings established fixed mourning periods for all ranks from the Son of Heaven to the scholar-official. Yet later yin-yang practitioners imposed so many taboos that people delay burial beyond the proper time, which grieves me greatly. I have personally tested whether the Grand Year pressing upon one's native year—which geomancers regard as most inauspicious—truly brings harm, and I found it causes no real damage." He then commanded the great minister Jeong Ieo and others to examine all writings, to preserve sound doctrine, to eliminate false teachings, to accord with the principles of sages and worthies, and to eradicate the festering disease of vulgar shamanism. They compiled this into a book titled "The Essential Guide to Auspicious Burial Days," which was promulgated throughout the realm. Thereafter the people's hearts found peace and royal law was illuminated anew. The fathers of our Eastern land no longer had to leave their deceased exposed to wind and rain, and the filial duty toward parents was fulfilled completely. True planning for posterity must follow the example of our Great King Taejong.

    The taboos regarding year, month, day, and hour have already been severed by our Great King Taejong. The false teachings claiming that mountains and waters determine national fortune and disaster should now be corrected by Your Highness. Your subject humbly beseeches Your Highness to follow distantly the correct Way of the ancient sages and worthies, and to follow near the noble intentions of our Great King Taejong. Permit worthy scholars to examine geomantic texts, taking the theories of Cheng Yi, Zhu Xi, and Sima Guang as their foundation, and eliminating all absurd and groundless claims—doing exactly as our Great King Taejong did.

    Further, Your Highness should establish the ultimate harmony, clarify the source of righteousness, devote effort to honoring virtue, and refuse to hear baseless words. Take Heaven's mandate as your mainspring and the people's hearts as your counterweight. Regard Heaven's bright command with reverence and fear the people's discontent. Strengthen governance and teachings to purify hearts and redirect the world's course. Let the light of this Way shine like the sun at noon, bringing forth an age of harmony and great peace to instruct posterity. Consolidate Heaven's mandate and bind the people's hearts, so that the nation's fortune becomes firm as stone and stable as the sacred mountain. This alone brings infinite blessings for ten thousand ages. What need have we to speak further of small matters regarding geomantic fortune and disaster?

    Your subject has reflected that the world often dismisses the words of Confucian scholars as bound to antiquity and unable to adapt to the present. Yet clinging to the past is itself a desire to illuminate the present. What your subject now presents, though it may seem to the worldly to be clinging to old ways, accords with the Way of sages and worthies in its refutation of false teachings, clarification of true doctrine, establishment of precedent, and instruction of posterity for the eternal preservation of Heaven's mandate. It cannot be said that it provides no small benefit.
